The expression in the image is a part of a trigonometric identity involving the sine function. It can be written in LaTeX format as:

\begin{aligned}
\sin \theta &= \frac{1}{2} \sin (2 \theta) \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \left(\frac{\pi}{4}\right)^2 \\
&= \frac{\sqrt{2}}{2}
\end{aligned}

This expression shows that the sine of an angle is equal to half the sine of twice that angle, with the angle being $\frac{\pi}{4}$ radians.
